Historically, hygiene has fluctuated dramatically â€” from the sophisticated public baths of the Roman world to long periods in which 
Europe largely abandoned such practices. This variability shows that hygiene is not an adaptive preventive tool, but a cultural baseline 
that societies may uphold or neglect.




Health of Environment & Infrastructure

Justification for the 3-4% Allocation â€” Health of Environment & Infrastructure
(refined with the origin of necessity)
Health of Environment & Infrastructureâ€™ receives a small, fixed allocation because it represents a contextual condition created by human 
development rather than a natural or biological preventive mechanism. Its relevance emerges from the way human populations organize, 
expand, and concentrate â€” whether in urban environments or simply through the increasing density of human life on Earth.
Several characteristics justify its limited but essential role:
It is not a natural preventive behavior.  
Its necessity arises from human-built environments and population density, not from innate biological processes.
It is a contextual condition, not an active practice.  
Environmental quality and infrastructure are external frameworks shaped collectively, not actions performed by individuals.
It cannot be personalized or adapted to individual needs.
Unlike adaptive preventive behaviors, environmental conditions do not adjust to individual profiles or needs.
It lacks functional synergy with active measures.  
Because it is not a behavior, it does not interact dynamically with other components of prophylaxis.
It cannot be individually optimized.  
Individuals benefit from healthier environments, but they cannot calibrate or adjust these conditions as part of a personal routine.
It is necessary because of societal development, not biological design.
As human populations grow and concentrate, shared infrastructure and environmental management become essential to maintaining baseline 
health.
For these reasons, an allocation of 3â€“4% accurately reflects its nature: a necessary background condition shaped by human 
civilization, yet limited in its direct preventive power.â€

